<DOC><DOCNO> AP890119-0134 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-19-89 1329EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Smoking     01-19 0173</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Norway-Smoking,0177</SECOND><HEAD>Anti-Smoking Groups See a Smoke-Free Norway</HEAD><DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Groups pressing for a smoke-free Norway bythe year 2000 have called for raising taxes on tobacco, banning itssale to people under 18 years old, and outlawing it in more publicplaces.   The plan, handed to Social Minister Tove Strand Gerhardsenearlier this week, builds on a law adopted last year forbiddingsmoking in public areas such as theater lobbies, bus or trainterminals and most offices.   The anti-smoking groups urged the government to adopt a newseries of measures in the next six years. They include ensuring asmoke-free environment in schools, increasing taxes on tobaccoproducts and outlawing their sale to people under 18.   The plan also calls for a smoking ban in prisons and other publicinstitutions, as well as in all hotel rooms and concert halls.   The government has endorsed the goal of making Norway smokelessby the end of the century. However, tobacco consumption in recentyears has increased by 500 tons per year.</TEXT></DOC>